Two separate issues here:

**1. `StaticResource` vs `DynamicResource`**

`StaticResource` resolves **once** at load time and never updates. For runtime theme switching, you must use `DynamicResource`:

```xml
<!-- Won't update at runtime -->
<Label TextColor="{StaticResource PrimaryTextColor}" />

<!-- Will update when the dictionary changes -->
<Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
```

Then swap themes by replacing the merged dictionary:

```csharp
var mergedDictionaries = Application.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
mergedDictionaries.Clear();
mergedDictionaries.Add(new DarkTheme()); // or LightTheme
```

**2. App restarting on Android dark mode change**

Android destroys and recreates the `Activity` on configuration changes like `uiMode`. Add this to your `MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
[Activity(
    Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme",
    ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.UiMode
        | ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
        | ConfigChanges.Orientation
        // ...other flags you already have
)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
}
```

This tells Android your app handles `UiMode` changes itself instead of restarting. You can then detect the system change and swap themes:

```csharp
public override void OnConfigurationChanged(Configuration newConfig)
{
    base.OnConfigurationChanged(newConfig);

    var isDark = (newConfig.UiMode & UiMode.NightMask) == UiMode.NightYes;
    // swap your ResourceDictionary here
}
```

**TL;DR:** Replace every `StaticResource` color binding with `DynamicResource`, and add `ConfigChanges.UiMode` to your `MainActivity` attribute.
